<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 43. Automatic Calculation of Adjustments to the Corset Pattern with Shoulders.</h1>
<p><strong>We need to do more calculations to adjust my standard pattern of a corset with shoulders and turn it into a lace top pattern. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image077.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let us use our Table for Automatic Calculation of Pattern Adjustments.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image079.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I put our client’s measurements in the corresponding boxes. All adjustment values are calculated automatically in an instant. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image081.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>There are certain fine points related to working with the corset pattern with shoulders. We will certainly talk about them. </strong></p>
<p><strong>As usual, I start from the centre front piece. I shift the fold line 0.5cm outwards to adjust the distance between the bust princess seams as suggested by the calculations. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image082.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let us apply all adjustments to the centre front piece first. </strong></p>
<p><strong>We must make the following adjustments: </strong></p>
<p>- Add 4.5cm to the Bust to Shoulder measurement, 2.5cm to the Bust to Shoulder Tip, and 3cm to the Shoulder to Shoulder Across Front.</p>
<p><strong>I draw a new shoulder line through the top points of the new measurement lines (points A and B). </strong></p>
<p><strong>The outer shoulder point (point C) </strong>lies at the intersection of the new shoulder line and the arc with a radius equal to the new Shoulder to Shoulder Across Front.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image083.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I mark Shoulder Length from point C. It is 9cm, line C-D. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image084.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the neck hole (line D-E).</strong> You can define the lowest neckline point (point E) more precisely if you know your client’s Centre Waist to Sternal Notch. In our case, I simply mark 4cm up from the top point of the fold line. It is almost the same value which was added to Bust to Shoulder.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image085.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Following the calculations, I add 1.4cm to the Clip toward Armscye and re-draw the armscye line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image086.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>We have adjusted all parts of the centre front piece apart from the princess seam line. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image087.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us move to the centre back piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong>My client’s Nape to Waist is 2cm longer than on the pattern. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image088.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Shoulder Slope Back also needs to be made 2cm longer (point A). </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image089.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I draw a new back shoulder line through point A. </strong></p>
<p>If you know your client’s Full Length Back, then you can simply connect point A with the side neck point indicated by this measurement.</p>
<p>Since I don’t know this measurement,<strong> I simply draw a new back shoulder line parallel to the old one. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image090.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I mark my client’s Shoulder Length from point A. It is 9cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image091.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the back neck.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image092.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I need to add 2cm to Width Back. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image093.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I connect the resulting end point of the measurement line with point A and get the new armscye line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image094.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let us move to the back princess seam line. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I shift it 0.2cm inwards at the bust line level, 0.3cm outwards at the under-bust line level and at the waistline level, and 0.3cm inwards at the stomach line level (bottom line). </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image095.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>And I re-draw the back princess seam line accordingly. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image096.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Next, I apply corresponding adjustments to the back princess seam line of the side back piece and re-draw it as well. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image097.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image098.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The new back princess seam lines look very natural. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I shift the back side seam line 1.1cm outwards. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image099.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The back pattern is basically finished! </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image100.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Adjustments to the side front piece are a whole different topic. </strong></p>
<p><strong>First of all, let us adjust the bust princess seam lines on the side front piece and centre front piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I shift it 0.3cm outwards at the waistline level and 0.3cm inwards at the stomach line level. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image101.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the bust princess seam lines correspondingly. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image102.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us examine the new bust princess seam lines. </strong></p>
<p>We don’t have to worry about curvy bust princess seam lines <strong>in our particular case</strong> because the top will be sewn with soft elastic lace fabric.</p>
<p><strong>But if you plan to sew with some kind of thick fabric, </strong>such as taffeta, for example, then I highly recommend you should not leave such curvy princess seam lines. One of the possible solutions is to transfer their adjustments to the side seam lines.</p>
<p>In other words, you can shift the back side seam lines and the front side seam lines 0.3cm outwards at the waistline level and 0.3cm inwards at the stomach line level.</p>
<p>This will slightly affect the side seam shape, of course, but not in a significant way.</p>
<p>Let me highlight it again: it is not worth doing all this if you sew with elastic fabric. You can safely keep those curvy princess seam lines because elastic fabric will naturally stretch out and settle correctly.</p>
<p><strong>In other words, you should carefully examine the new princess seam lines based on automatically calculated pattern adjustments and adjust them manually if you have some doubts. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image103.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I shift the front side seam line 2.3cm outwards. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image104.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>We have approached a very curious part of our calculations. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The table says that we must make a dart with a width of 0.7cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Before talking about why and where exactly this dart arose, let us look at the Clip measurements. </strong></p>
<p><strong>It follows from the calculations that we need to add 1.4cm to the Clip toward Armscye. </strong>I prolong the bust princess seam line of the side front piece by that value.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image105.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Now, if we simply connect the new clip point with the top point of the new side seam line and re-draw the armscye, there will be too much tension in the bust princess seam above the bust line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image106.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The suggested dart with a width of 0.7cm shown in the table is supposed to lower the tension in this area of the bust princess seam. </strong></p>
<p><strong>What I do is draw a perpendicular line of 0.7cm going up from the new clip point and re-draw the top part of the bust princess seam. This is how I account for the new dart width. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image107.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let me give you some important advice. </strong></p>
<p><strong>If you are sewing a corset with shoulders instead of a soft top </strong>and you decide to put bones in the cups, then you should be extremely careful when you are easing in the fabric under the half-circle cup bone. Even if you ease in as little as 1cm of fabric or less, I still highly recommend you should leave some excess seam allowance along the top part of the bust princess seams, i.e. above the bust line. Sometimes, you have to undo the princess seam and let it out a little because of too much tension caused by the easing-in.</p>
<p><strong>And this is why you should be very careful when easing in cups on corsets with shoulders (especially, large-size corsets). Leave some extra space on the seam allowances of the bust princess seams.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image108.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Now I want to talk about some other peculiar features of our garment. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image109.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Let me remind you that a 19cm distance between bust princess seams is somewhat critical for a Bust Circumference of 98cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Why can we still afford it in this particular garment? </strong>It is only because the lace top has a low V-neck.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image110.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>When the bride puts the lace top on, its front halves will slightly come apart,</strong> literally by just one centimeter, and it will be enough for a normal distance between bust princess seams.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image111.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>There is another interesting detail. </strong></p>
<p><strong>There is no under-bust dart on the pattern of a corset with shoulders which we use for the lace top. </strong>As the result, the lace top may not cling to the corset properly in the low neckline area.</p>
<p><strong>You can add an under-bust dart either by making a slit in the bust area of the top and then decorating it with lace or by pulling the fabric in different directions along the neckline edge when sewing the top. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image112.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>There are also certain modelling lines on our lace top pattern which require some attention. </strong></p>
<p><strong>First of all, there is a kind of a collar line which goes up over the shoulder and behind the neck. </strong>This requires that you slightly lengthen the shoulder line of the centre front piece and adjust the shape of the neckline in the neck area.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image113.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Then, there is also a modelling line forming the small short sleeve. </strong></p>
<p>You need to prolong the shoulder line of <strong>the centre front piece </strong>by about 3-4cm toward the arm, then go down by about 1.5cm or 2cm depending on desired sleeve length, and connect it with the armscye.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image114.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The centre back piece should be adjusted accordingly. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image115.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And, finally, I raise the back neck line of the centre back piece by a couple of centimeters to shape a kind of a stand-up collar. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2043.files/image116.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I never make any special calculations or drafts for such additional modelling lines. They can all be fine-tuned right on the client. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The last thing I wanted to say: </strong></p>
<p><strong>I highly recommend that you sew both mock-ups (a corset and a top) to align and even out the bottom edges of the two garments. </strong></p>
<p>You will align their waistlines, even out the length, draw the desired shape of the bottom edge, and trim it accordingly on both garments in one go.</p>
<p><strong>This way all pieces will form an even well-aligned bottom edge. </strong></p>
<p>Next, you will rip up the mock-ups, put the pieces over your paper patterns, and copy the new lines.</p>
<p><strong>After doing this, you can safely cut your garment from expensive fabric. </strong></p>

